  "beats": [
    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "This is Liam, in for Bear. The largest z component of orbital angular momentum is ell h bar. So why is the total squared value ell times ell plus one, rather than ell squared?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "remotion",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "provenance": "proven-core/ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "command": "Why is L² = ℓ(ℓ+1)ℏ² instead of ℓ²ℏ²?",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS — ANGULAR MOMENTUM",
            "segment": "Where the Plus One Comes From",
            "greeting": "Hallo, Liam",
            "runningText": "testing the top rung…",
            "output": [
              "Lz,max = ℓℏ.",
              "Noncommuting transverse components still contribute."
            ],
            "folderLabel": "@NikBearBrown",
            "modelLabel": "Fable 5",
            "effortLabel": "High"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B01.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.9,
      "build": {
        "status": "VIDEO",
        "src": "media/B01.mp4",
        "filled_by": "media",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:33:06"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "The tempting argument is simple. Square the maximum z component and get ell squared h bar squared. But the total-angular-momentum eigenvalue is ell times ell plus one h bar squared.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.29,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:33:06"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "The mistake is treating the total magnitude as though the state could point exactly along z. Why must the total exceed its largest measurable z component?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.17,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:33:06"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "For fixed ell, the magnetic quantum number m climbs in integer steps from minus ell to plus ell. At the top rung, m equals ell and L z gives ell h bar.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.69,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:33:06"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "But L squared contains L x squared, L y squared, and L z squared. In the top L z state, the average transverse components vanish, yet their squared contributions do not.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "decompose"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.92,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:33:06"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 5,
      "narration_text": "The commutator creates the missing contribution.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 3.26,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:33:06"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 14,
      "narration_text": "Use the identity L squared equals L minus L plus, plus L z squared, plus h bar L z. That last term appears because L x and L y do not commute. For ordinary numbers, it would be absent.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.01,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:33:06"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 5,
      "narration_text": "Now impose the top-rung condition: raising once more must give zero.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 4.69,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:33:06"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "On the top state, L plus annihilates the state, so L minus L plus contributes zero. L z squared gives ell squared h bar squared, and h bar L z gives ell h bar squared. Add them: ell times ell plus one.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.14,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:33:06"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Geometrically, the total length is h bar times the square root of ell times ell plus one, while its largest z projection is ell h bar. The vector cannot align exactly with the axis.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.09,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:33:06"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "For a d orbital, ell equals two. The naive result is four h bar squared. The correct result is two times three, or six h bar squared. The five allowed m values are minus two through plus two.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.95,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:33:06"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "The plus one is not an empirical patch. It is the noncommutativity of angular-momentum components made visible in the eigenvalue.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.36,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B12.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:33:06"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Your turn. At ell equals three, compare ell squared with ell times ell plus one. Which term comes from h bar L z on the top rung?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "remotion",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
